\begin_layout Section*
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Among Helmut Ohley's design goals for 18FR was to produce a game with a
 lower rate of bankruptcies than 1830.
 However 18FR had a very similar rate of player-bankruptcies to 1830 in
 our group.
 18FR-RCE's primary goals are to reduce the bankruptcy rate to well below
 50% of games, while also providing for more interesting train and track
 management sub-games without significantly increasing play-time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section*
Designer's notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
18FR is a fine and interesting game, but it has significant problems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\noun on
Cie de la Ceinture
\noun default
 (the cheapest private company in 18FR) controls access to eastern Paris.
 This is so strong and valuable that many players feel that it should be
 simply bought at the first opportunity; it is too large a reward to be
 determined by random seating order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\noun on
Cie de St Etienne
\noun default
's special power is largely useless.
 It is too far away from Paris, and there are too many tokens and possibly
 blocking track between it and Paris to be interesting.
 As a result the only real value for the 
\noun on
Cie de St Etienne
\noun default
 was for selling it to a major company.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Bankruptcies are no more uncommon in 18FR than in 1830.
 Stylistically I prefer games to end in bankruptcy no more than 25%-30%
 of the time at the outside, thus preserving interest in late-game planning,
 Diesel-train runs etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Diesel routes tended to be small, usually in the 40fr - 55fr range, making
 for an extended end-game that over-valued diesel trains as they ran for
 8+ Operating Rounds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some of the changes made in 18FR-RCE and supporting reasons:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Track is rarely built to Brest in 18FR.
 It is in the wrong direction, has annoying towns along the way, and isn't
 worth enough.
 Sometimes it is built in the very late game for Diesel runs, but that is
 still rare as Brest is a dead-end.
 An additional hex was added beside Brest and the track on Brest changed
 in order to allow Diesels to run to and through Brest.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In order to solve already mentioned problem with the 
\noun on
Cie de la Ceinture
\noun default
, a new private company was added to the bottom of the private-auction.
 This had the side effect of also increasing the number of private companies,
 which changes the balance and timing points of the traditional 1830 private
 auction in interesting ways, most especially for larger player counts.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Additionally the new private company was given a small special power of
 an extra one-time tile-lay.
 A less invasive change was considered for shuffling the order, values and
 powers of the current private companies (in particular moving the 
\noun on
Cie de Bologne - Amiens
\noun default
 to block the hexes currently controlled by the 
\noun on
Cie de la Ceinture
\noun default
), but was discarded as being too invasive when combined with all the other
 adjustments then required.
 Instead a new private company was added.
 The new private company is so cheap and its revenue so small, that those
 numbers are mostly insignificant.
 However the extra tile-lay significantly changes the balance of tempo and
 positioning among the various companies in interesting ways, most especially
 n the companies north of Paris, even more so when combined with the 
\emph on
\noun on
Cie de le Havre
\emph default
\noun default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\noun on
Cie de Paris - St Germain
\noun default
's hex was changed from a single town to a double town.
 This increases the number of double-town hexes to match 1830 and makes
 the exact choice and timing of the track-tile placed there by the 
\noun on
Cie de Paris - St Germain
\noun default
 more interesting.
 The presence of the extra town and its track additionally makes the Double-O
 at Le Mans frequently strategically interesting in the early game for those
 planning late-game strategic track connections through the 
\noun on
Cie de Paris - St Germain
\noun default
's hex.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The number of yellow #57 tiles was increased as we found that ~80% of 18FR
 games had one or more companies starting with no tile to place on their
 home-station, and this was thought too common to be interesting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The increased early focus on Le Mans provides a timing challenge for the
 Double-O at Calais.
 They frequently want the same brown tile, and to later upgrade to the new
 gray Double-O tile.
 That tension also increases the possibility that the green #59 Double-O
 tile may not be available for the 
\noun on
Chemin de Fer du Midi
\noun default
's home station (in its new location) when it starts (much like the Erie
 in 1830).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The additional station marker for Lille in the brown tiles simply balances
 the positional power of the 3-station brown tile for Lyon, while providing
 for a back-door around the key hex at D17 and to the gray Double-O upgrade
 should it be placed at Calais.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\noun on
Cie de St Etienne
\noun default
 was moved to Le Havre in order to provide more conflict to the north of
 Paris, where previously only the 
\noun on
Chemin de Fer du Nord 
\noun default
and
\noun on
 Chemins de Fer de l'Ouest
\noun default
 fought.
 A track-stub and town were added to Le Havre in order to force the orientation
 of the #57 track tile so that the 
\noun on
Cie de Le Havre
\noun default
 wouldn't be too strong.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The new 
\noun on
Cie De le Havre
\noun default
